{"title_page": "Winter cluster", "text_new": "In [[beekeeping]], a '''winter cluster''' is a well-defined cluster of [[honey bee]]s that forms inside a [[Beehive (beekeeping)|beehive]] when the air temperature dips below 10 to 14 \u00b0C (50 to 57 F).  Honey bees are one of but a few kinds of insects that survive the winter as a colony.  As the outside air temperature decreases the winter cluster becomes tighter and more compact.  The bees cling tightly together on the [[Honeycomb|combs]] in the hive.  The temperature within the winter cluster remains remarkably warm regardless of the outside air temperature.  Larger clusters ([[basketball]] size) have a better chance for survival than smaller clusters ([[softball]] size).  The winter cluster within the hive must move throughout the winter to reach the available honey stored in the combs. <ref>Charles D.Owens [http://www.beesource.com/pov/usda/thermology/techbulletin1429.htm THE THERMOLOGY OF WINTERING HONEY BEE COLONIES] </ref>\n\nSome die-off is expected during the winter.  In extended cold weather periods, the incidence of [[Diseases of the honey bee#Nosema disease|Nosema disease]] increases and the cluster may weaken as many bees begin dying off.<ref>Basil Furgala. 1975. Chapter XVI; Fall Management and the Wintering of Productive Colonies. In: ''The hive and the honeybee''. Dept. of Entomology, [[University of Minnesota]], Dadant.</ref>\n\n==Honey bee brood nest==\n{{main|Bee brood}}\nIn subtropical climates, bees may not form a winter cluster at all.  [[Worker bee]]s forage and [[queen bee|queens]] lay eggs almost year-round.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn the temperate zones, winter temperatures dip below 12 \u00b0C (54 \u00b0F) for extended periods.  All brood rearing stops for some period during the winter.  In early spring, brood rearing resumes inside the winter cluster when the queens starts to lay eggs again.  Once a broodnest is established, the cluster must maintain a steady temperature between 34.5 to 36.7 \u00b0C (94.1 - 98.0 \u00b0F) inside the cluster.  If the temperature in areas of the brood nest dips too low the brood could die - also called [[Diseases of the honey bee#Chilled brood|chilled brood]].{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Western honey bee behavior]]\n\n{{Bee-stub}}\n", "text_old": "In [[beekeeping]], a '''winter cluster''' is a well-defined cluster of [[honey bee]]s that forms inside a [[Beehive (beekeeping)|beehive]] when the air temperature dips below 10 to 14 \u00b0C (50 to 57 F).  Honey bees are one of but a few kinds of insects that survive the winter as a colony.  As the outside air temperature decreases the winter cluster becomes tighter and more compact.  The bees cling tightly together on the [[Honeycomb|combs]] in the hive.  The temperature within the winter cluster remains remarkably warm regardless of the outside air temperature.  Larger clusters ([[basketball]] size) have a better chance for survival than smaller clusters ([[softball]] size).  The winter cluster within the hive must move throughout the winter to reach the available honey stored in the combs. <ref>Charles D.Owens [http://www.beesource.com/pov/usda/thermology/techbulletin1429.htm THE THERMOLOGY OF WINTERING HONEY BEE COLONIES] </ref>\n\nSome die-off is expected during the winter.  In extended cold weather periods, the incidence of [[Diseases of the honey bee#Nosema disease|Nosema disease]] increases and the cluster may weaken as many bees begin dying off.<ref>Basil Furgala. 1975. Chapter XVI; Fall Management and the Wintering of Productive Colonies. In: ''The hive and the honeybee''. Dept. of Entomology, [[University of Minnesota]], Dadant.</ref>\n\n==Honey bee brood nest==\n{{main|Bee brood}}\nIn subtropical climates, bees may not form a winter cluster at all.  [[Worker bee]]s forage and [[queen bee|queens]] lay eggs almost year-round.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn the temperate zones, winter temperatures dip below 12 \u00b0C (54 \u00b0F) for extended periods.  All brood rearing stops for some period during the winter.  In early spring, brood rearing resumes inside the winter cluster when the queens starts to lay eggs again.  Once a broodnest is established, the cluster must maintain a steady temperature between 34.5 to 36.7 \u00b0C (94.1 - 98.0 \u00b0F) inside the cluster.  If the temperature in areas of the brood nest dips too low the brood dies - also called [[Diseases of the honey bee#Chilled brood|chilled brood]].{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Western honey bee behavior]]\n\n{{Bee-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cornersss", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHoney bee brood nest", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winter_cluster"}
{"title_page": "Damsel of Cyprus", "text_new": "The '''Damsel of Cyprus''' (born c. 1177), possibly named '''Beatrice''' or '''Maria''',{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} was the daughter of [[Isaac Komnenos of Cyprus|Isaac Komnenos]], emperor of [[Byzantine Cyprus|Cyprus]], and an [[Kingdom of Cilicia|Armenian]] princess. She was her father's sole heiress. Her given name is not known with certainty and she is known by convention as the \"Damsel of Cyprus\".\n\nShe was a hostage in the [[Principality of Antioch]] from 1182 until at least 1184. She was captured in 1191 during a brief war between her father and King [[Richard I of England]]. She remained an English prisoner, although treated well, until 1194. During her captivity she travelled throughout the Holy Land, Italy and France. After her release, she remained in France. In 1199 or 1200, she married Count [[Raymond VI of Toulouse]], becoming his fourth wife. They divorced by late 1202 or early 1203, when she married [[Thierry of Flanders (flourished 1197\u20131207)|Thierry of Flanders]], who attempted to claim Cyprus on her behalf. After this failed venture, the couple went to Armenia. Her fate thereafter is unknown.\n\n==Name==\nThe Damsel of Cyprus is specified in contemporary chronicles and documents as \"Isaac's daughter\" (''filia Isaaci''){{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=157}} or the \"daughter of the emperor [of Cyprus]\" (''filia imperatoris [Cypri]'',{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=158}} ''fille de l'Empereor de Chypre'').{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=171}} The chronicles that record her second marriage do not name her husband, either, although his identity can be deduced from the information given.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=169\u2013170}}\n\nWipertus Rudt de Collenberg suggests that Isaac's daughter may be the ''domicella'' (damsel) Beatrice who is listed first among the female beneficiaries of the will of [[Joan of England, Queen of Sicily|Joan of England]], queen of Sicily and third wife of Raymond of Toulouse, in 1199. She received the large sum of 200 [[Mark (currency)|marks]], while the other ladies received 140 marks (Alice), 100 (Helysabeth), 60 (Philippa) and 15 (Malekakxa). She and Alice also inherited two coffers at Verdun and their contents. The title ''domicella'' (diminutive of lady) implies an unmarried girl of noble birth. The name Beatrice would have been appropriate for Isaac's daughter, since both of her maternal great-grandparents bore the name, [[Beatrice of Saone]] and the daughter of Count [[Hugh I, Count of Rethel|Hugh of Rethel]], as well as her great-great-grandmother, the daughter of [[Constantine I, Prince of Armenia|Constantine I of Armenia]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=174\u2013175}}\n\nGeorge Jeffery calls her Maria, without explanation. Annette Parks uses Beatrice, provisionally.{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}}\n\n==Childhood==\nThe Damsel was born probably in 1177 or 1178. She had a brother, name also unknown. Her parents were probably married in 1175 or 1176.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|loc=Tableaux g\u00e9n\u00e9alogiques I and II}} Her father, who was born between 1155 and 1160, had recently been appointed governor of [[Cilicia]] (between 1173 and 1175). Her mother, whose name is also unknown, was the daughter of Prince [[Thoros II of Armenia]] and Isabella, daughter of Count [[Joscelin II of Edessa]]. The Damsel was thus related to the ruling families of [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantium]] and Armenia as well as one of the leading families of crusader [[Outremer]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=130}}\n\nAfter fighting broke out between Byzantium and Armenia, Isaac was captured. This happened perhaps as early as 1176,{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} certainly by 1180.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=131}} In 1182, he was handed over to Prince [[Bohemond III of Antioch]] in a prisoner exchange. He gave his children as hostages to Bohemond in order to obtain his release to raise his ransom. When the final payment of 30,000 [[bezant]]s was stolen by pirates, he refused to re-raise it and the Damsel and her brother thus remained hostages at the court of the prince of Antioch for another two years, when they were released for reasons of state.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=133\u2013134}} This was probably around 1184,{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} but [[Roger of Howden]] places it around the time of the [[Siege of Jerusalem (1187)|fall of Jerusalem]] in 1187.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=133\u2013134}}\n\nThe death of her brother between 1187 and 1191, left the Damsel the sole heir of her father. According to [[Benedict of Peterborough]], Isaac killed his wife and then his son, but this is extremely unlikely.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=135}} His first wife had probably died by 1184 or else opted to remain in her homeland, in which case he would have obtained a divorce. By 1191, he had remarried to an illegitimate daughter of King [[William I of Sicily]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=145}}\n\n==English captivity==\nBetween 1 and 22 May 1191, Isaac Komnenos was involved in a conflict with the English contingent of the [[Third Crusade]]. He threatened [[Berengaria of Navarre|Berengaria]], the fianc\u00e9e of King [[Richard I of England]], and Richard promptly landed troops and took [[Limassol]] while Isaac retreated after some skirmishes. On 16 May, the two met and Richard demanded that Isaac pay an indemnity, put a mixed force of cavalry and infantry at his disposal and hand over his daughter and his new wife as hostages. In return, Richard would [[enfeoff]] him with Cyprus. Isaac refused these terms and retreated north. On 21 May, Richard attacked the [[Kyrenia Castle|castle of Kyrenia]], having learned that Isaac's daughter was there. The Damsel, who was only about fourteen years old, came out of the castle, fell at Richard's feet \"out of fear\" and surrendered both herself and the fortress. Richard took her hand and helped her to her feet.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}}\n\nAccording to the ''[[Itinerarium Regis Ricardi|Itinerarium regis Ricardi]]'', on learning of his daughter's capture Isaac despaired \"because he loved her dearly\".{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}} Roger of Howden is even stronger, writing \"he loved [her] more than any other creature\".{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} He surrendered on 22 May.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}} There is no basis for the claim by [[H. W. C. Davis]] that Richard threatened to kill his captive to induce Isaac's surrender.{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} On 1 June, Richard quit Cyprus, taking his prisoners with him to [[Akko|Acre]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}}\n\nThe ''Itinerarium'' describes her as a \"young little thing\" (''juvenculam parvulam'') at the time of her capture. The ''[[Chronica anonymi Laudunensis canonici]]'' also describes her as handsome (''speciosa''). [[Ralph de Diceto]] even thought it necessary to condemn those who accused Richard of an attraction to his captive. According to the ''Itinerarium'', Richard had her put \"in custody, lest she be carried off\" (''in custodiam ne forte raperetur''), which implies physical confinement.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=156}} The ''[[Ernoul|Chronique d'Ernoul]]'' and the ''[[Eracles|Histoire d'Eracles]]'' claim that she was imprisoned in [[Margat]] with her father, but Ralph says that she was \"retained in honorable custody in the royal chamber with the two queens\"<!-- (''cum duabus reginis in thalamo regis honorifice custodiam retinuit'')-->, Richard's queen, Berengaria, and his sister Joan, dowager queen of Sicily.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=157}} The poet [[Ambroise]], commenting on her capture, also says she was sent to the queen not for safekeeping but for her education:\n<poem>\n:And his young daughter a most fair\n:And lovely maid of beauty rare\n:Had sent her to the queen that she\n:Might well be taught and fittingly.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=156}}\n</poem>\nThe chronicles of the Third Crusade note the continued presence of \"Isaac's daughter\" with the two queens. The three spent Christmas 1191 at [[Toron]] and afterwards visited [[Jerusalem]]. They embarked to return to Europe on 29 September 1192. They went first to Sicily, where the second wife of Isaac had also returned. There they learned that Richard had been imprisoned by Duke [[Leopold V, Duke of Austria|Leopold V of Austria]]. Escorted by [[Stephen de Turnham]], they went on to Rome, where they were present on 9 April 1193.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=157}}\n\nRoger of Howden records that Pope [[Celestine III]] honorably received the emperor of Cyprus's daughter. They remained in Rome until June. They left under the escort of Cardnial [[Melior (cardinal)|Melior]] and went by way of [[Pisa]] and [[Genoa]] to [[Marseille]], where they were met by King [[Alfonso II of Aragon]], whose brother [[Ramon Berenguer III, Count of Provence|Raymond Berengar]] was the count of Provence. Alfonso escorted them through Provence to the [[County of Toulouse]], where they were escorted by Raymond of Saint-Gilles, the future Count [[Raymond VI of Toulouse|Raymond VI]], who would later marry both Joan and the Damsel. They arrived in [[Poitiers]] in Richard's [[Duchy of Aquitaine]] towards the end of 1193.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=158}}\n\n==Release==\nOn 14 February 1193 at [[W\u00fcrzburg]], Leopold of Austria signed a treaty with [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor]]. By its terms, Leopold would hand Richard over to Henry, who would hold him prisoner until Isaac and his daughter were released. Leopold and Isaac were second cousins. On 28 March, Richard was handed over and the treaty came into force. On 26 June, Richard signed an agreement with Henry that incorporated the treaty of W\u00fcrzburg in its entirety. The Damsel was to be handed over to Leopold as guardian at the same time as Richard's niece, [[Eleanor, Fair Maid of Brittany|Eleanor of Brittany]], who was betrothed to Leopold's son [[Frederick I, Duke of Austria (Babenberg)|Frederick]]. The negotiations also envisioned the future marriage of the Damsel to Frederick's younger brother, [[Leopold VI, Duke of Austria|Leopold VI]], her third cousin. Richard was released on 2 February 1194, presumably a date corresponding in some way to the liberation of Isaac.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=159\u2013162}}\n\nIn 1194, the Damsel was joined by Eleanor of Brittany at the court of Berengaria and Joan, which travelled between [[Chinon]] and [[Rouen]]. An entry in the [[pipe rolls]] of the [[Exchequer of Normandy]] for 11 September 1194 records a payment of 168 pounds and 12 shillings to \"the daughter of the Count of Brittany and the daughter of the Emperor of Cyprus and their [joint] household\". In the autumn of 1194, Duke Leopold complained to Richard that the girls had not yet been sent to him.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=163}}\n\nIn December 1194, the Damsel of Cyprus and Eleanor of Brittany departed for [[Vienna]] in the company of [[Baldwin of B\u00e9thune]]. When the latter learned of the death of Leopold on 31 December, he turned the party around on his own initiative and returned to Normandy. The duke's sons had no interest in pursuing the marriages their father had envisioned for them and they died with him. The party arrived back in Normandy in the spring of 1196. This coincided with the death of her father in late 1195 or early 1196{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=163\u2013164}}\n\n==Marriages==\nNothing is known of the Damsel's movements for the next five years.<!-- It is possible but unlikely that she joined her relatives in [[Montpellier]]. Her great aunt was [[Eudokia Komnene, wife of William VIII of Montpellier|Eudokia Komnene]], the divorc\u00e9e of [[William VIII of Montpellier]] who had become a nun at [[Aniane]].--> She probably remained attached to Joan, who in October 1196 became the third wife of Raymond VI of Toulouse. She died on 24 September 1199, having spent the last part of her marriage in northern France. The ''Histoire d'Eracles'' seems to suppose that the Damsel remained a prisoner down to 1199, which perception may be owed to her continued residence with Joan. After the death of Joan, she became Raymond's fourth wife, probably in 1199 or 1200. The editorial remark in the ''[[Recueil des historiens des croisades]]'' that she was a mere concubine is without foundation. The marriage is recorded in the ''Eracles'' and by [[Pierre de Vaux-Cernay]], who mistakenly dates it to 1193\u20131196.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=166\u2013167}} The marriage was over by 1203 (probably by October 1202<!--when Raymond was in the Holy Land?-->) and Raymond married a fifth time in January 1204. The reasons for the end of her first marriage are unknown.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=169\u2013170}}\n\nThe Damsel's second marriage took place at [[Marseille]] in the winter of 1202\u20131203. She wed [[Thierry of Flanders (flourished 1197\u20131207)|Thierry of Flanders]], one of the commanders of the Flemish fleet of the [[Fourth Crusade]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=169\u2013170}} It was probably her intention to claim Cyprus. The fleet did not take part in the [[Sack of Constantinople|attack on Constantinople]] but sailed directly to the Holy Land. It stopped in Cyprus, where Thierry with the support of his men demanded the island in the name of his wife. Rebuffed by the actual king of Cyprus, [[Aimery of Cyprus|Aimery]], the majority of the crusaders, including Thierry and his wife, went on to Armenia. This is the last that is heard of the Damsel. Thierry was in Constantinople in 1207, but it is not known if his wife was with him.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=172\u2013173}}\n\nThere is possibly a literary echo of Thierry and the Damsel's claim on Cyprus in the ''[[Vida (Occitan literary form)|vida]]'' (short biography) of the troubadour [[Peire Vidal]], who addressed poems to Eudokia and William VIII of Montpellier and may well have crossed paths with the daughter of Isaac.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=172\u2013173}}{{sfn|Fraser|2006|p=28}} The ''vida'' is a short, fictional account written probably around 1240:\n{{quote|...he took a Greek woman who had been given to him in marriage in Cyprus; and he claimed that she was the niece of the Emperor of Constantinople and through her he should have the right to the Empire. He gathered together all he could obtain to make ships, in order to set out to conquer the empire.{{sfn|Fraser|2006|p=27}}}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em|indenty=yes}}\n*{{cite thesis |ref=harv |url=https://tel.archives-ouvertes.fr/tel-01927994/document |first=\u00c9douard |last=Baraton |title=La Romanie orientale: l'empire de Constantinople et ses avatars au Levant \u00e0 l'\u00e9poque des Croisades |institution=Normandie Universit\u00e9 |year=2018 |type=PhD diss.}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |editor-first=Veronica Mary |editor-last=Fraser |title=The Songs of Peire Vidal: Translation and Commentary |publisher=Peter Lang |year=2006}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |authorlink=John Gillingham |first=John |last=Gillingham |title=Richard I |publisher=Yale University Press |year=1999}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=George |last=Jeffery |title=Cyprus Under an English King in the Twelfth Century: The Adventures of Richard I and the Crowning of His Queen in the Island |publisher=Zeno |year=1973 |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Annette P. |last=Parks |chapter=Rescuing the Maidens from the Tower: Recovering the Stories of Two Female Political Hostages |pages=279\u2013292 |publisher=Ashgate |year=2010 |title=Feud, Violence and Practice: Essays in Medieval Studies in Honor of Stephen D. White |editor1=Belle S. Tuten |editor2=Tracey L. Billado}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=har |first=W. H. |last=Rudt de Collenberg |title=L'empereur Isaac de Chypre et sa fille (1155\u20131207) |journal=Byzantion |volume=38 |issue=1 |year=1968 |pages=123\u2013179}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:1170s births]]\n[[Category:13th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:Komnenos dynasty]]\n[[Category:Byzantine Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Cypriot people of Armenian descent]]\n[[Category:Cypriot people of French descent]]\n[[Category:12th-century Byzantine women]]\n[[Category:13th-century Byzantine women]]\n[[Category:12th-century Armenian women]]\n[[Category:13th-century Armenian women]]\n[[Category:Holy Land travellers]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Fourth Crusade]]\n[[Category:Countesses of Toulouse]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Damsel of Cyprus''' (born c. 1177), possibly named '''Beatrice''' or '''Maria''',{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} was the daughter of [[Isaac Komnenos of Cyprus|Isaac Komnenos]], emperor of [[Byzantine Cyprus|Cyprus]], and an [[Kingdom of Cilicia|Armenian]] princess. She was her father's sole heiress. Her given name is not known with certainty and she is known by convention as the \"Damsel of Cyprus\".\n\nShe was a hostage in the [[Principality of Antioch]] from 1182 until at least 1184. She was captured in 1191 during a brief war between her father and King [[Richard I of England]]. She remained an English prisoner, although treated well, until 1194. During her captivity she travelled throughout the Holy Land, Italy and France. After her release, she remained in France. In 1199 or 1200, she married Count [[Raymond VI of Toulouse]], becoming his fourth wife. They divorced by late 1202 or early 1203, when she married [[Thierry of Flanders (flourished 1197\u20131207)|Thierry of Flanders]], who attempted to claim Cyprus on her behalf. After this failed venture, the couple went to Armenia. Her fate thereafter is unknown.\n\n==Name==\nThe Damsel of Cyprus is specified in contemporary chronicles and documents as \"Isaac's daughter\" (''filia Isaaci''){{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=157}} or the \"daughter of the emperor [of Cyprus]\" (''filia imperatoris [Cypri]'',{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=158}} ''fille de l'Empereor de Chypre'').{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=171}} The chronicles that record her second marriage do not name her husband, either, although his identity can be deduced from the information given.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=169\u2013170}}\n\nWipertus Rudt de Collenberg suggests that Isaac's daughter may be the ''domicella'' (damsel) Beatrice who is listed first among the female beneficiaries of the will of [[Joan of England, Queen of Sicily|Joan of England]], queen of Sicily and third wife of Raymond of Toulouse, in 1199. She received the large sum of 200 [[Mark (currency)|marks]], while the other ladies received 140 marks (Alice), 100 (Helysabeth), 60 (Philippa) and 15 (Malekakxa). She and Alice also inherited two coffers at Verdun and their contents. The title ''domicella'' (diminutive of lady) implies an unmarried girl of noble birth. The name Beatrice would have been appropriate for Isaac's daughter, since both of her maternal great-grandparents bore the name, [[Beatrice of Saone]] and the daughter of Count [[Hugh I, Count of Rethel|Hugh of Rethel]], as well as her great-great-grandmother, the daughter of [[Constantine I, Prince of Armenia|Constantine I of Armenia]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=174\u2013175}}\n\nGeorge Jeffery calls her Maria, without explanation. Annette Parks uses Beatrice, provisionally.{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}}\n\n==Childhood==\nThe Damsel was born probably in 1177 or 1178. She had a brother, name also unknown. Her parents were probably married in 1175 or 1176.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|loc=Tableaux g\u00e9n\u00e9alogiques I and II}} Her father, who was born between 1155 and 1160, had recently been appointed governor of [[Cilicia]] (between 1173 and 1175). Her mother, whose name is also unknown, was the daughter of Prince [[Thoros II of Armenia]] and Isabella, daughter of Count [[Joscelin II of Edessa]]. The Damsel was thus related to the ruling families of [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantium]] and Armenia as well as one of the leading families of crusader [[Outremer]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=130}}\n\nAfter fighting broke out between Byzantium and Armenia, Isaac was captured. This happened perhaps as early as 1176,{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} certainly by 1180.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=131}} In 1182, he was handed over to Prince [[Bohemond III of Antioch]] in a prisoner exchange. He gave his children as hostages to Bohemond in order to obtain his release to raise his ransom. When the final payment of 30,000 [[bezant]]s was stolen by pirates, he refused to re-raise it and the Damsel and her brother thus remained hostages at the court of the prince of Antioch for another two years, when they were released for reasons of state.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=133\u2013134}} This was probably around 1184,{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} but [[Roger of Howden]] places it around the time of the [[Siege of Jerusalem (1187)|fall of Jerusalem]] in 1187.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=133\u2013134}}\n\nThe death of her brother between 1187 and 1191, left the Damsel the sole heir of her father. According to [[Benedict of Peterborough]], Isaac killed his wife and then his son, but this is extremely unlikely.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=135}} His first wife had probably died by 1184 or else opted to remain in her homeland, in which case he would have obtained a divorce. By 1191, he had remarried to an illegitimate daughter of King [[William I of Sicily]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=145}}\n\n==English captivity==\nBetween 1 and 22 May 1191, Isaac Komnenos was involved in a conflict with the English contingent of the [[Third Crusade]]. He threatened [[Berengaria of Navarre|Berengaria]], the fianc\u00e9e of King [[Richard I of England]], and Richard promptly landed troops and took [[Limassol]] while Isaac retreated after some skirmishes. On 16 May, the two met and Richard demanded that Isaac pay an indemnity, put a mixed force of cavalry and infantry at his disposal and hand over his daughter and his new wife as hostages. In return, Richard would [[enfeoff]] him with Cyprus. Isaac refused these terms and retreated north. On 21 May, Richard attacked the [[Kyrenia Castle|castle of Kyrenia]], having learned that Isaac's daughter was there. The Damsel, who was only about fourteen years old, came out of the castle, fell at Richard's feet \"out of fear\" and surrendered both herself and the fortress. Richard took her hand and helped her to her feet.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}}\n\nAccording to the ''[[Itinerarium Regis Ricardi|Itinerarium regis Ricardi]]'', on learning of his daughter's capture Isaac despaired \"because he loved her dearly\".{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}} Roger of Howden is even stronger, writing \"he loved [her] more than any other creature\".{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} He surrendered on 22 May.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}} There is no basis for the claim by [[H. W. C. Davis]] that Richard threatened to kill his captive to induce Isaac's surrender.{{sfn|Parks|2010|pp=286\u2013289}} On 1 June, Richard quit Cyprus, taking his prisoners with him to [[Akko|Acre]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=148\u2013151}}\n\nThe ''Itinerarium'' describes her as a \"young little thing\" (''juvenculam parvulam'') at the time of her capture. The ''[[Chronica anonymi Laudunensis canonici]]'' also describes her as handsome (''speciosa''). [[Ralph de Diceto]] even thought it necessary to condemn those who accused Richard of an attraction to his captive. According to the ''Itinerarium'', Richard had her put \"in custody, lest she be carried off\" (''in custodiam ne forte raperetur''), which implies physical confinement.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=156}} The ''[[Ernoul|Chronique d'Ernoul]]'' and the ''[[Eracles|Histoire d'Eracles]]'' claim that she was imprisoned in [[Margat]] with her father, but Ralph says that she was \"retained in honorable custody in the royal chamber with the two queens\"<!-- (''cum duabus reginis in thalamo regis honorifice custodiam retinuit'')-->, Richard's queen, Berengaria, and his sister Joan, dowager queen of Sicily.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=157}} The poet [[Ambroise]], commenting on her capture, also says she was sent to the queen not for safekeeping but for her education:\n<poem>\n:And his young daughter a most fair\n:And lovely maid of beauty rare\n:Had sent her to the queen that she\n:Might well be taught and fittingly.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=156}}\n</poem>\nThe chronicles of the Third Crusade note the continued presence of \"Isaac's daughter\" with the two queens. The three spent Christmas 1191 at [[Toron]] and afterwards visited [[Jerusalem]]. They embarked to return to Europe on 29 September 1192. They went first to Sicily, where the second wife of Isaac had also returned. There they learned that Richard had been imprisoned by Duke [[Leopold V, Duke of Austria|Leopold V of Austria]]. Escorted by [[Stephen de Turnham]], they went on to Rome, where they were present on 9 April 1193.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=157}}\n\nRoger of Howden records that Pope [[Celestine III]] honorably received the emperor of Cyprus's daughter. They remained in Rome until June. They left under the escort of Cardnial [[Melior (cardinal)|Melior]] and went by way of [[Pisa]] and [[Genoa]] to [[Marseille]], where they were met by King [[Alfonso II of Aragon]], whose brother [[Ramon Berenguer III, Count of Provence|Raymond Berengar]] was the count of Provence. Alfonso escorted them through Provence to the [[County of Toulouse]], where they were escorted by Raymond of Saint-Gilles, the future Count [[Raymond VI of Toulouse|Raymond VI]], who would later marry both Joan and the Damsel. They arrived in [[Poitiers]] in Richard's [[Duchy of Aquitaine]] towards the end of 1193.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=158}}\n\n==Release==\nOn 14 February 1193 at [[W\u00fcrzburg]], Leopold of Austria signed a treaty with [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor]]. By its terms, Leopold would hand Richard over to Henry, who would hold him prisoner until Isaac and his daughter were released. Leopold and Isaac were second cousins. On 28 March, Richard was handed over and the treaty came into force. On 26 June, Richard signed an agreement with Henry that incorporated the treaty of W\u00fcrzburg in its entirety. The Damsel was to be handed over to Leopold as guardian at the same time as Richard's niece, [[Eleanor, Fair Maid of Brittany|Eleanor of Brittany]], who was betrothed to Leopold's son [[Frederick I, Duke of Austria (Babenberg)|Frederick]]. The negotiations also envisioned the future marriage of the Damsel to Frederick's younger brother, [[Leopold VI, Duke of Austria|Leopold VI]], her third cousin. Richard was released on 2 February 1194, presumably a date corresponding in some way to the liberation of Isaac.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=159\u2013162}}\n\nIn 1194, the Damsel was joined by Eleanor of Brittany at the court of Berengaria and Joan, which travelled between [[Chinon]] and [[Rouen]]. An entry in the [[pipe rolls]] of the [[Exchequer of Normandy]] for 11 September 1194 records a payment of 168 pounds and 12 shillings to \"the daughter of the Count of Brittany and the daughter of the Emperor of Cyprus and their [joint] household\". In the autumn of 1194, Duke Leopold complained to Richard that the girls had not yet been sent to him.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|p=163}}\n\nIn December 1194, the Damsel of Cyprus and Eleanor of Brittany departed for [[Vienna]] in the company of [[Baldwin of B\u00e9thune]]. When the latter learned of the death of Leopold on 31 December, he turned the party around on his own initiative and returned to Normandy. The duke's sons had no interest in pursuing the marriages their father had envisioned for them and they died with him. The party arrived back in Normandy in the spring of 1196. This coincided with the death of her father in late 1195 or early 1196{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=163\u2013164}}\n\n==Marriages==\nNothing is known of the Damsel's movements for the next five years.<!-- It is possible but unlikely that she joined her relatives in [[Montpellier]]. Her great aunt was [[Eudokia Komnene, wife of William VIII of Montpellier|Eudokia Komnene]], the divorc\u00e9e of [[William VIII of Montpellier]] who had become a nun at [[Aniane]].--> She probably remained attached to Joan, who in October 1196 became the third wife of Raymond VI of Toulouse. She died on 24 September 1199, having spent the last part of her marriage in northern France. The ''Histoire d'Eracles'' seems to suppose that the Damsel remained a prisoner down to 1199, which perception may be owed to her continued residence with Joan. After the death of Joan, she became Raymond's fourth wife, probably in 1199 or 1200. The editorial remark in the ''[[Recueil des historiens des croisades]]'' that she was a mere concubine is without foundation. The marriage is recorded in the ''Eracles'' and by [[Pierre de Vaux-Cernay]], who mistakenly dates it to 1193\u20131196.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=166\u2013167}} The marriage was over by 1203 (probably by October 1202<!--when Raymond was in the Holy Land?-->) and Raymond married a fifth time in January 1204. The reasons for the end of her first marriage are unknown.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=169\u2013170}}\n\nThe Damsel's second marriage took place at [[Marseille]] in the winter of 1202\u20131203. She wed [[Thierry of Flanders (flourished 1197\u20131207)|Thierry of Flanders]], one of the commanders of the Flemish fleet of the [[Fourth Crusade]].{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=169\u2013170}} It was probably her intention to claim Cyprus. The fleet did not take part in the [[Sack of Constantinople|attack on Constantinople]] but sailed directly to the Holy Land. It stopped in Cyprus, where Thierry with the support of his men demanded the island in the name of his wife. Rebuffed by the actual king of Cyprus, [[Aimery of Cyprus|Aimery]], the majority of the crusaders, including Thierry and his wife, went on to Armenia. This is the last that is heard of the Damsel. Thierry was in Constantinople in 1207, but it is not known if his wife was with him.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=172\u2013173}}\n\nThere is possibly a literary echo of Thierry and the Damsel's claim on Cyprus in the ''[[Vida (Occitan literary form)|vida]]'' (short biography) of the troubadour [[Peire Vidal]], who addressed poems to Eudokia and William VIII of Montpellier and may well have crossed paths with the daughter of Isaac.{{sfn|Rudt de Collenberg|1968|pp=172\u2013173}}{{sfn|Fraser|2006|p=28}} The ''vida'' is a short, fictional account written probably around 1240:\n{{quote|...he took a Greek woman who had been given to him in marriage in Cyprus; and he claimed that she was the niece of the Emperor of Constantinople and through her he should have the right to the Empire. He gathered together all he could obtain to make ships, in order to set out to conquer the empire.{{sfn|Fraser|2006|p=27}}}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em|indenty=yes}}\n*{{cite thesis |ref=harv |url=https://tel.archives-ouvertes.fr/tel-01927994/document |first=\u00c9douard |last=Baraton |title=La Romanie orientale: l'empire de Constantinople et ses avatars au Levant \u00e0 l'\u00e9poque des Croisades |institution=Normandie Universit\u00e9 |year=2018 |type=PhD diss.}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |editor-first=Veronica Mary |editor-last=Fraser |title=The Songs of Peire Vidal: Translation and Commentary |publisher=Peter Lang |year=2006}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |authorlink=John Gillingham |first=John |last=Gillingham |title=Richard I |publisher=Yale University Press |year=1999}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=George |last=Jeffery |title=Cyprus Under an English King in the Twelfth Century: The Adventures of Richard I and the Crowning of His Queen in the Island |publisher=Zeno |year=1973 |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Annette P. |last=Parks |chapter=Rescuing the Maidens from the Tower: Recovering the Stories of Two Female Political Hostages |pages=279\u2013292 |publisher=Ashgate |year=2010 |title=Feud, Violence and Practice: Essays in Medieval Studies in Honor of Stephen D. White |editor1=Belle S. Tuten |editor2=Tracey L. Billado}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=har |first=W. H. |last=Rudt de Collenberg |title=L'empereur Isaac de Chypre et sa fille (1155\u20131207) |journal=Byzantion |volume=38 |issue=1 |year=1968 |pages=123\u2013179}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:1170s births]]\n[[Category:13th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:Komnenos dynasty]]\n[[Category:12th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:13th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:Holy Land travellers]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Fourth Crusade]]\n[[Category:Countesses of Toulouse]]\n", "name_user": "Srnec", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damsel_of_Cyprus"}
{"title_page": "Customs and etiquette in Chinese dining", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n{{howto|date=April 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Cuisine of China}}\n\n'''Customs and etiquette in Chinese dining''' are the traditional behaviors observed while eating in [[Greater China]]. Traditional [[Han Chinese|Han]] customs have spread throughout [[East Asian cultural sphere|East Asia]] to varying degrees, with some regions sharing a few aspects of formal dining, which has ranged from guest seating to paying the bill.\n\n==Table and place settings==\n[[File:HK Sai Ying Pun \u540d\u661f\u6d77\u9bae\u9152\u5bb6 Star Seafood Restaurant round table March-2012 Ip4.jpg|thumb|right|Typical place settings before a meal is served]]\nIn most traditional Chinese dining, dishes are shared [[Communal bowl|communally]]. Although both square and rectangular tables are used for small groups of people, round tables are preferred for large groups, particularly in restaurants, in order to permit easy sharing. [[Lazy Susan]] turntables are a common feature at the center of larger tables, to facilitate passing of serving dishes. \n\nA basic [[place setting]] consists of a small teacup; a large plate with a small, empty rice bowl; a set of chopsticks, usually on the right of the plate; and a soup spoon. Additions may include a chopstick rest or holder, a large water or wine glass, and a smaller glass for ''[[baijiu]]''. Occasionally a small shallow dish is left for each diner, to hold a small amount of a condiment or sauce.\n\nAt homes and low-end restaurants, napkins may consist of [[Tissue paper|paper tissues]] or occasionally must be provided by the diner. High restaurants often provide cloth napkins similar to Western dining as part of the place settings.\n\nUnlike some Western restaurants, powdered salt, pepper, or sugar are rarely provided at the table. Sometimes bottles of soy sauce, vinegar, hot sauce, or other condiments are available.[[Black vinegar]] is popular in the north of China as a dipping sauce, particularly for dumplings.<ref>{{Citation|title=Black vinegar|date=2020-04-14|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Black_vinegar&oldid=950867267|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Formal seating order ===\nThere is a specific [[Seating plan|seating order]] to every [[formal dinner]], based on seniority and organizational hierarchy. The [[seat of honor]], reserved for the host or the oldest person, is usually the position in the center facing east or facing the entrance to the room. Guests with higher status then sit in close proximity to the seat of honor, while those with lower positions sit further away. The least pretigious seat is generally the one nearest to the kitchen entrance or service door.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internations.org/hong-kong-expats/guide/15908-culture-shopping-recreation/dining-in-hong-kong-etiquette-15914|title=Dining in Hong Kong: Etiquette|website=www.internations.org}}</ref>\n\n==Sequencing of a meal==\nWide variations exist throughout China, but the vast majority of full-course dinners are very similar in terms of timing and dishes.\n\n===Beverages===\n[[File:Chinese teapot.JPG|thumb|right|An 18th century Chinese porcelain hand painted blue and white teapot]]\nHot tea is almost always provided, either in advance of the diners being seated or immediately afterward. It can be consumed at leisure throughout the meal. Hot or cold water is sometimes served, but tea is the default beverage. A verbal \"thank you\" ({{zh|s=\u8c22\u8c22|p=xiexie|labels=no}}) may be offered to the server pouring a refill or, if in the middle of a conversation where it would be rude to interrupt the speaker, the table may be [[Chinese tea culture#Finger tapping|tapped twice with two bent fingers]] instead.\n\n===Appetizers===\nAppetizers are the first items presented. Two or more small dishes are brought to the table, holding boiled unsalted peanuts, salted roasted peanuts, crispy fried noodles, or similar dishes. These may be consumed while ordering the main courses, or while waiting for other dishes to arrive.\n\n===Soup===\nA hot soup may be served as one of the dishes, usually near the beginning of the meal. For small meals, especially at home, it may replace the diners' beverage entirely.\n\n===Main courses===\n{{see also|Dim sum}}\nUnlike Western-style meals, there are usually multiple main dishes which are sampled by all the diners; usually there is one communally-shared dish ordered per person seated at a table. A celebratory event such as a graduation or wedding often features over ten dishes, often an odd number for good luck.\n \nWhite steamed rice is provided in small bowls and food is often placed over it, flavoring it with their sauces. The rice is consumed little by little along with the other dishes and not separately, unless the diner remains hungry after the last dish has been removed.\n\n===Final course===\nNear the end of the meal, a starchy, filling dish such as noodles, [[jiaozi|Chinese dumplings]], or ''[[baozi]]'' is sometimes served, to ensure that guests are fully satiated. In extremely formal settings, only a small amount of this final dish is taken by the diners, to avoid implying that the host was not sufficiently generous in planning the meal.\n\n===Dessert===\nInformal meals may not have a dessert course at all, or offer sweet foods that are particular favorites of the diners. Fresh fruit (often slices of citrus) or fresh or canned pineapple are often offered in restaurants.\n\nOther common desserts are [[tapioca]] or [[rice pudding]], or a hot or cold soup flavored with [[red bean soup|sweet red beans]]. Ice cream may be offered, often flavored with [[ginger]], [[Red bean ice|sweet red beans]], or a delicate tea.\n\n[[Fortune cookie]]s are rarely offered by authentic Chinese restaurants, even in North America where they were invented. They are considered a lightweight amusement, suitable for informal gatherings of close friends and family. Fancier restaurants may offer mints or occasionally chocolates as breath fresheners.\n\n==Manners and customs ==\nEating is a dominant aspect of [[Chinese culture]], and eating out is one of the most common ways to honor guests, socialize, and deepen friendships.<ref name=\"Dob\">Dobsons, Richard. ''China Cycle'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=1HwBFSfy_f0C&pg=RA1-PA20 p. 20]. 2006. 8 Feb 2010.</ref>\n\nProper [[etiquette]] is very important to traditional Chinese people, who feel good manners invite [[luck]], but boorish conduct brings [[shame]]. Although many [[Mao Zedong|Maoist]] programs tried to curtail traditional social practices, today table etiquette is again taken as an indication of educational status and good upbringing. For example, a child misusing their chopsticks at a formal dinner might embarrass their family, who are responsible for teaching the child.<ref name=\"Dob\"/><ref name=\"Cha\"/>\n\n===Personal behavior===\n{{See also|Eating utensil etiquette}}\nSince [[chopsticks]] (and [[spoon]]s) are used in place of [[fork]]s and [[knives]], [[Chinese cuisine]] tends to serve dishes in bite-size pieces or employ cooking techniques that render dishes such as fish or ''[[hong shao rou]]'' soft enough to be picked apart easily.<ref name=\"Inn\">Inness, Sherrie. \"Home Cooking .\" Kitchen Culture in America: Popular Representations of Food, Gender, and Race (2001): 14. Web. 21 Jan 2010. <https://books.google.com/books?id=Ik7w8jQhzHMC&pg=RA4-PA14&dq=chinese+table+etiquette&lr=&ei=7flXS7G0IaaolQTd3rCwAw&cd=31#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20etiquette&f=false>.</ref> Some common etiquette is:<ref name=\"Hu\"/><ref name=\"Zho\"/><ref name=\"Sue\">Fox, Sue. \"Chapter 19: On the Go: Travel Manners for Land, Sea, and Air .\" Etiquette for Dummies (2007): 319. Web. 21 Jan 2010. <https://books.google.com/books?id=HGno_t1crwwC&pg=PA319&dq=Dining+Etiquette+china&lr=&cd=34#v=onepage&q=Dining%20Etiquette%20china&f=false>.</ref>\n\nChopsticks are only used for picking up food. One should not spear food with chopsticks although people sometimes do it if the food is too slippery. Chopsticks are not to be used to point at people, pick teeth, bang the bowls, move the bowls, nor to be chewed on or waved around. They should be held so that the ends are even, and never separated in any way (such as holding one in each hand). \n\nWhen not in use, chopsticks should be left on chopstick rests when provided, or placed across the bowl or plate. They should never be left sticking upright out of food, evoking images of incense or \"joss\" sticks used ceremoniously at funerals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture-4-travel.com/chopstick-etiquette.html|title=Chinese Chopstick Etiquette|work=Culture-4-Travel.com}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally, a diner is supposed to hold the chopsticks in the right hand and with the left hand either hold down the bowl on the table or pick it up so that it is near the mouth, or at least put the left hand on the table; eating with the chopsticks in the left hand or steadily with only one hand on the table is perceived as unproper table manners.{{Why?|reason=Why is this perceived as rude behaviour? The fact that this way to handle food is traditionally claimed and perceived to be rude does not mean the perception is correct. There is no concrete evidence that this perception is correct, and that both hands should be used when eating is in fact no rule or law; perception is a more correct word.|date=February 2020}}{{Fix|text=reliable source??}}{{dubious|date=January 2020}} However, that perception has started to fade away in modern time.{{when?|date=March 2020}}{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} It is, however, never considered rude to lift a rice bowl with one hand to scoop rice into the mouth using chopsticks in the other hand.\n\nCondiments, such as [[soy sauce]], [[duck sauce]], or [[sesame oil]], are sometimes served in small shallow dishes to allow pieces of food to be dipped as desired. They may not be routinely provided at high-quality restaurants; the assumption is that perfectly-prepared food needs no condiments, and the quality of the food can be best appreciated as prepared by the master chef.\n\nIt is considered virtuous for diners to not leave any bit of wasted food on their plates or bowls. If significant amounts of untouched food are left over in the serving dishes after a meal, it is often considered a compliment to the chef to request that it be packaged for takeout, to be enjoyed later at home.\n\n===Inviting guests===\nAlthough individual households may have their own house rules, the Chinese traditions used to welcome guests are largely the same throughout the country.<ref name=\"Mor\">Morse, Edward. ''Glimpses of China and Chinese Homes'', p. 65. Kegan Paul, Int'l (New York), 2001.</ref><ref name=\"Hu\">Hu Wenzhong & al. ''Encountering the Chinese: A Guide for Americans'', pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=gInx5N7gGg4C&pg=PA39 35\u201340]. 1999. Accessed 21 Jan 2010.</ref> There are common rules for inviting guests over.<ref name=\"Cha\">Chai, May-Lee & al. ''China A to Z'', p. 104. Plume Books (New York), 2007.</ref><ref name=\"Hu\"/><ref name=\"Zho\">Zhou, Cathy. ''Chinese Etiquette and Culture'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=0TV8ebayzNUC&pg=PA26 p. 26]. 2005. Accessed 21 Jan 2010.</ref>\n\nCommunal eating is very common in China, encompassing informal meals among close friends and family, as well as more formal meals and banquets to celebrate special occasions. In addition to providing opportunities for socializing, shared meals allow the diners to sample a wider range of dishes than if they were ordering individually.\n\n===Communal eating===\n[[File:Spoon and chopsticks.jpg|thumb|upright|Serving chopsticks (''gongkuai'') on the far right, personal chopsticks (''putongkuai'' or ''sikuai'') in the middle, and a spoon. Serving chopsticks are usually more ornate and longer than the personal ones.]]\nThere appears to be no Chinese word for communal eating and using one's personal chopsticks in the serving dish. However, at some formal meals, there may be pairs of communal serving chopsticks ({{lang|zh|\u516c\u7b77}}, ''gongkuai''). These are sets of chopsticks specifically for shared dishes only. Often, these will be distinct from the ''putongkuai'' ({{lang|zh|\u666e\u901a\u7b77}}, regular chopsticks) or ''sikuai'' ({{lang|zh|\u79c1\u7b77}}, personal chopsticks) in that they will be longer and more ornate. There will sometimes be one set of communal chopsticks per dish or one set per course. The ratio varies.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Jt6u8RZw51cC&pg=PA109&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false 9][https://books.google.com/books?id=0TV8ebayzNUC&pg=PA26&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false 10][https://books.google.com/books?id=npxUXbUg6uUC&pg=PA164&dq=chopstick+manners&hl=en#v=onepage&q=chopsticks&f=false 11]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=32uyAAAAIAAJ&q=chopstick+etiquette&dq=chopstick+etiquette&hl=en 12]</ref> If there are no ''gongkuai'' set on the table, it is never rude to request that they be provided; others will just think that you are a stickler for formality and good manners.\n\nIt is also considered extremely rude to dig for a choice food morsel on the serving plate instead of picking up the piece that is closest to the diner, thus demonstrating fairness and sharing with others. The shunned practice is sometimes called \"digging one's grave\". Likewise, it is impolite to hoard or take most of a dish until it has been offered to everyone and the other diners have had a chance to sample it. For this reason, it is common to take a smaller amount from the dishes on the first round, and to keep the other diners in mind when taking a larger second helping.\n\nThe last piece of food on a communal dish is never served to oneself without asking for permission. When offered the last bit of food, it may sometimes be considered rude to refuse the offer.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}{{dubious|date=February 2020}} \n\n===Lazy Susan (turntable)===\n[[File:Lazy Susan.jpg|thumb|A Lazy Susan in use]]\nA [[Lazy Susan]] turntable is a large circular rotating platform placed at the center of a table, and used to easily share a large number of dishes among the diners. A Lazy Susan can be made from many materials, but most often they are constructed of glass, wood, or plastic.\n\nIt is typical for all the dishes for each course to be brought out together and placed around the perimeter of the Lazy Susan. It the turntable is large, a decorative centerpiece may occupy the center, since any food placed there would be out of reach of a seated diner. Alternatively, shared table condiments such as soy sauce, hot sauce, vinegar, or sesame oil may be located at the center.\n\nIf the dishes come out one at a time or if there is some special delicacy, they are typically served to the guest of honor first and then rotated clockwise around the table. The host will often wait to serve himself last. Dishes should typically not be removed from the Lazy Susan and placed on the table: at most, one should hold the dish aloft while serving and then return it to its place on the tray. One should try to avoid moving the Lazy Susan even slightly when someone is in the act of transferring food from the dishes to their plate or bowl. \n\n===Alcohol===\nWater and other non-alcoholic beverages may be consumed at any time. However, in formal settings, alcohol should only be consumed during [[toast (honor)|toasts]]. A modest toast may be followed by a single sip of wine or swallow of beer, but a ''baijiu'' toast is often ended with ''Ganbei!'' ({{lang|zh|\u5e72\u676f}}), an exhortation to drain the glass. Ideally, glasses are refilled immediately following a toast in preparation for the next.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn informal settings, individuals may order their preferred drinks. Carbonated beverages or beer are often ordered, although many diners may be satisfied with tea or hot water.\n\n==Bill (check)==\nThe bill for the meal (often call the \"check\") is presented at the end of the meal, after all the food and drinks have been served. In most restaurants in Chinese countries, there is no [[gratuity|tip]] expected unless it is explicitly posted. Usually if there is a tip required, it will already be added to the bill. However, in Chinese restaurants in North America tips are usually expected, as is customary in other restaurants of the region.\n\nIt is a common sight for families to dispute over who pays the bill, as the person paying thereby demonstrates generosity, sincerity, and dominance. If somebody organizes a meal and invites the guests, that person is usually accorded the honor of paying for the event.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Customs and etiquette in Japanese dining]]\n*[[Chinese culture|Culture of China]]\n*[[Chinese cuisine]]\n*[[Etiquette in Asia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n<!--\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=Jt6u8RZw51cC&pg=PA109&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false Ref. 8]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=Jt6u8RZw51cC&pg=PA109&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false Ref. 9]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=0TV8ebayzNUC&pg=PA26&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false Ref. 10]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=npxUXbUg6uUC&pg=PA164&dq=chopstick+manners&hl=en#v=onepage&q=chopsticks&f=false Ref. 11 page 164]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=32uyAAAAIAAJ&q=chopstick+etiquette&dq=chopstick+etiquette&hl=en Ref. 12 page 69-71]\n-->\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/28/business/global/28iht-busnav28.html?partner=rssnyt&emc=rss In China, Social Evenings Are Considered Part of the Business Routine]\n* [https://ac.els-cdn.com/S2352618115000657/1-s2.0-S2352618115000657-main.pdf?_tid=698dab50-0114-4938-a7f6-58bddca2b29a&acdnat=1528346775_0fcf187161655a2b6fe6aeb18defa85f Food, eating behavior, and culture in Chinese society]\n* [http://confuciusmag.com/chinese-dining-etiquette Chinese dining etiquette]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chinese Table Manner}}\n[[Category:Etiquette by region|Chinese dining]]\n[[Category:Dining etiquette]]\n[[Category:Chinese cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n{{howto|date=April 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Cuisine of China}}\n\n'''Customs and etiquette in Chinese dining''' are the traditional behaviors observed while eating in [[Greater China]]. Traditional [[Han Chinese|Han]] customs have spread throughout [[East Asian cultural sphere|East Asia]] to varying degrees, with some regions sharing a few aspects of formal dining, which has ranged from guest seating to paying the bill.\n\n==Table and place settings==\n[[File:HK Sai Ying Pun \u540d\u661f\u6d77\u9bae\u9152\u5bb6 Star Seafood Restaurant round table March-2012 Ip4.jpg|thumb|right|Typical place settings before a meal is served]]\nIn most traditional Chinese dining, dishes are shared [[Communal bowl|communally]]. Although both square and rectangular tables are used for small groups of people, round tables are preferred for large groups, particularly in restaurants, in order to permit easy sharing. [[Lazy Susan]] turntables are a common feature at the center of larger tables, to facilitate passing of serving dishes. \n\nA basic [[place setting]] consists of a small teacup; a large plate with a small, empty rice bowl; a set of chopsticks, usually on the right of the plate; and a soup spoon. Additions may include a chopstick rest or holder, a large water or wine glass, and a smaller glass for ''[[baijiu]]''. Occasionally a small shallow dish is left for each diner, to hold a small amount of a condiment or sauce.\n\nAt homes and low-end restaurants, napkins may consist of [[Tissue paper|paper tissues]] or occasionally must be provided by the diner. High restaurants often provide cloth napkins similar to Western dining as part of the place settings.\n\nUnlike some Western restaurants, powdered salt, pepper, or sugar are rarely provided at the table. Sometimes bottles of soy sauce, vinegar, hot sauce, or other condiments are available.\n\n=== Formal seating order ===\nThere is a specific [[Seating plan|seating order]] to every [[formal dinner]], based on seniority and organizational hierarchy. The [[seat of honor]], reserved for the host or the oldest person, is usually the position in the center facing east or facing the entrance to the room. Guests with higher status then sit in close proximity to the seat of honor, while those with lower positions sit further away. The least pretigious seat is generally the one nearest to the kitchen entrance or service door.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internations.org/hong-kong-expats/guide/15908-culture-shopping-recreation/dining-in-hong-kong-etiquette-15914|title=Dining in Hong Kong: Etiquette|website=www.internations.org}}</ref>\n\n==Sequencing of a meal==\nWide variations exist throughout China, but the vast majority of full-course dinners are very similar in terms of timing and dishes.\n\n===Beverages===\n[[File:Chinese teapot.JPG|thumb|right|An 18th century Chinese porcelain hand painted blue and white teapot]]\nHot tea is almost always provided, either in advance of the diners being seated or immediately afterward. It can be consumed at leisure throughout the meal. Hot or cold water is sometimes served, but tea is the default beverage. A verbal \"thank you\" ({{zh|s=\u8c22\u8c22|p=xiexie|labels=no}}) may be offered to the server pouring a refill or, if in the middle of a conversation where it would be rude to interrupt the speaker, the table may be [[Chinese tea culture#Finger tapping|tapped twice with two bent fingers]] instead.\n\n===Appetizers===\nAppetizers are the first items presented. Two or more small dishes are brought to the table, holding boiled unsalted peanuts, salted roasted peanuts, crispy fried noodles, or similar dishes. These may be consumed while ordering the main courses, or while waiting for other dishes to arrive.\n\n===Soup===\nA hot soup may be served as one of the dishes, usually near the beginning of the meal. For small meals, especially at home, it may replace the diners' beverage entirely.\n\n===Main courses===\n{{see also|Dim sum}}\nUnlike Western-style meals, there are usually multiple main dishes which are sampled by all the diners; usually there is one communally-shared dish ordered per person seated at a table. A celebratory event such as a graduation or wedding often features over ten dishes, often an odd number for good luck.\n \nWhite steamed rice is provided in small bowls and food is often placed over it, flavoring it with their sauces. The rice is consumed little by little along with the other dishes and not separately, unless the diner remains hungry after the last dish has been removed.\n\n===Final course===\nNear the end of the meal, a starchy, filling dish such as noodles, [[jiaozi|Chinese dumplings]], or ''[[baozi]]'' is sometimes served, to ensure that guests are fully satiated. In extremely formal settings, only a small amount of this final dish is taken by the diners, to avoid implying that the host was not sufficiently generous in planning the meal.\n\n===Dessert===\nInformal meals may not have a dessert course at all, or offer sweet foods that are particular favorites of the diners. Fresh fruit (often slices of citrus) or fresh or canned pineapple are often offered in restaurants.\n\nOther common desserts are [[tapioca]] or [[rice pudding]], or a hot or cold soup flavored with [[red bean soup|sweet red beans]]. Ice cream may be offered, often flavored with [[ginger]], [[Red bean ice|sweet red beans]], or a delicate tea.\n\n[[Fortune cookie]]s are rarely offered by authentic Chinese restaurants, even in North America where they were invented. They are considered a lightweight amusement, suitable for informal gatherings of close friends and family. Fancier restaurants may offer mints or occasionally chocolates as breath fresheners.\n\n==Manners and customs ==\nEating is a dominant aspect of [[Chinese culture]], and eating out is one of the most common ways to honor guests, socialize, and deepen friendships.<ref name=\"Dob\">Dobsons, Richard. ''China Cycle'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=1HwBFSfy_f0C&pg=RA1-PA20 p. 20]. 2006. 8 Feb 2010.</ref>\n\nProper [[etiquette]] is very important to traditional Chinese people, who feel good manners invite [[luck]], but boorish conduct brings [[shame]]. Although many [[Mao Zedong|Maoist]] programs tried to curtail traditional social practices, today table etiquette is again taken as an indication of educational status and good upbringing. For example, a child misusing their chopsticks at a formal dinner might embarrass their family, who are responsible for teaching the child.<ref name=\"Dob\"/><ref name=\"Cha\"/>\n\n===Personal behavior===\n{{See also|Eating utensil etiquette}}\nSince [[chopsticks]] (and [[spoon]]s) are used in place of [[fork]]s and [[knives]], [[Chinese cuisine]] tends to serve dishes in bite-size pieces or employ cooking techniques that render dishes such as fish or ''[[hong shao rou]]'' soft enough to be picked apart easily.<ref name=\"Inn\">Inness, Sherrie. \"Home Cooking .\" Kitchen Culture in America: Popular Representations of Food, Gender, and Race (2001): 14. Web. 21 Jan 2010. <https://books.google.com/books?id=Ik7w8jQhzHMC&pg=RA4-PA14&dq=chinese+table+etiquette&lr=&ei=7flXS7G0IaaolQTd3rCwAw&cd=31#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20etiquette&f=false>.</ref> Some common etiquette is:<ref name=\"Hu\"/><ref name=\"Zho\"/><ref name=\"Sue\">Fox, Sue. \"Chapter 19: On the Go: Travel Manners for Land, Sea, and Air .\" Etiquette for Dummies (2007): 319. Web. 21 Jan 2010. <https://books.google.com/books?id=HGno_t1crwwC&pg=PA319&dq=Dining+Etiquette+china&lr=&cd=34#v=onepage&q=Dining%20Etiquette%20china&f=false>.</ref>\n\nChopsticks are only used for picking up food. One should not spear food with chopsticks although people sometimes do it if the food is too slippery. Chopsticks are not to be used to point at people, pick teeth, bang the bowls, move the bowls, nor to be chewed on or waved around. They should be held so that the ends are even, and never separated in any way (such as holding one in each hand). \n\nWhen not in use, chopsticks should be left on chopstick rests when provided, or placed across the bowl or plate. They should never be left sticking upright out of food, evoking images of incense or \"joss\" sticks used ceremoniously at funerals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture-4-travel.com/chopstick-etiquette.html|title=Chinese Chopstick Etiquette|work=Culture-4-Travel.com}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally, a diner is supposed to hold the chopsticks in the right hand and with the left hand either hold down the bowl on the table or pick it up so that it is near the mouth, or at least put the left hand on the table; eating with the chopsticks in the left hand or steadily with only one hand on the table is perceived as unproper table manners.{{Why?|reason=Why is this perceived as rude behaviour? The fact that this way to handle food is traditionally claimed and perceived to be rude does not mean the perception is correct. There is no concrete evidence that this perception is correct, and that both hands should be used when eating is in fact no rule or law; perception is a more correct word.|date=February 2020}}{{Fix|text=reliable source??}}{{dubious|date=January 2020}} However, that perception has started to fade away in modern time.{{when?|date=March 2020}}{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} It is, however, never considered rude to lift a rice bowl with one hand to scoop rice into the mouth using chopsticks in the other hand.\n\nCondiments, such as [[soy sauce]], [[duck sauce]], or [[sesame oil]], are sometimes served in small shallow dishes to allow pieces of food to be dipped as desired. They may not be routinely provided at high-quality restaurants; the assumption is that perfectly-prepared food needs no condiments, and the quality of the food can be best appreciated as prepared by the master chef.\n\nIt is considered virtuous for diners to not leave any bit of wasted food on their plates or bowls. If significant amounts of untouched food are left over in the serving dishes after a meal, it is often considered a compliment to the chef to request that it be packaged for takeout, to be enjoyed later at home.\n\n===Inviting guests===\nAlthough individual households may have their own house rules, the Chinese traditions used to welcome guests are largely the same throughout the country.<ref name=\"Mor\">Morse, Edward. ''Glimpses of China and Chinese Homes'', p. 65. Kegan Paul, Int'l (New York), 2001.</ref><ref name=\"Hu\">Hu Wenzhong & al. ''Encountering the Chinese: A Guide for Americans'', pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=gInx5N7gGg4C&pg=PA39 35\u201340]. 1999. Accessed 21 Jan 2010.</ref> There are common rules for inviting guests over.<ref name=\"Cha\">Chai, May-Lee & al. ''China A to Z'', p. 104. Plume Books (New York), 2007.</ref><ref name=\"Hu\"/><ref name=\"Zho\">Zhou, Cathy. ''Chinese Etiquette and Culture'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=0TV8ebayzNUC&pg=PA26 p. 26]. 2005. Accessed 21 Jan 2010.</ref>\n\nCommunal eating is very common in China, encompassing informal meals among close friends and family, as well as more formal meals and banquets to celebrate special occasions. In addition to providing opportunities for socializing, shared meals allow the diners to sample a wider range of dishes than if they were ordering individually.\n\n===Communal eating===\n[[File:Spoon and chopsticks.jpg|thumb|upright|Serving chopsticks (''gongkuai'') on the far right, personal chopsticks (''putongkuai'' or ''sikuai'') in the middle, and a spoon. Serving chopsticks are usually more ornate and longer than the personal ones.]]\nThere appears to be no Chinese word for communal eating and using one's personal chopsticks in the serving dish. However, at some formal meals, there may be pairs of communal serving chopsticks ({{lang|zh|\u516c\u7b77}}, ''gongkuai''). These are sets of chopsticks specifically for shared dishes only. Often, these will be distinct from the ''putongkuai'' ({{lang|zh|\u666e\u901a\u7b77}}, regular chopsticks) or ''sikuai'' ({{lang|zh|\u79c1\u7b77}}, personal chopsticks) in that they will be longer and more ornate. There will sometimes be one set of communal chopsticks per dish or one set per course. The ratio varies.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Jt6u8RZw51cC&pg=PA109&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false 9][https://books.google.com/books?id=0TV8ebayzNUC&pg=PA26&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false 10][https://books.google.com/books?id=npxUXbUg6uUC&pg=PA164&dq=chopstick+manners&hl=en#v=onepage&q=chopsticks&f=false 11]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=32uyAAAAIAAJ&q=chopstick+etiquette&dq=chopstick+etiquette&hl=en 12]</ref> If there are no ''gongkuai'' set on the table, it is never rude to request that they be provided; others will just think that you are a stickler for formality and good manners.\n\nIt is also considered extremely rude to dig for a choice food morsel on the serving plate instead of picking up the piece that is closest to the diner, thus demonstrating fairness and sharing with others. The shunned practice is sometimes called \"digging one's grave\". Likewise, it is impolite to hoard or take most of a dish until it has been offered to everyone and the other diners have had a chance to sample it. For this reason, it is common to take a smaller amount from the dishes on the first round, and to keep the other diners in mind when taking a larger second helping.\n\nThe last piece of food on a communal dish is never served to oneself without asking for permission. When offered the last bit of food, it may sometimes be considered rude to refuse the offer.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}{{dubious|date=February 2020}} \n\n===Lazy Susan (turntable)===\n[[File:Lazy Susan.jpg|thumb|A Lazy Susan in use]]\nA [[Lazy Susan]] turntable is a large circular rotating platform placed at the center of a table, and used to easily share a large number of dishes among the diners. A Lazy Susan can be made from many materials, but most often they are constructed of glass, wood, or plastic.\n\nIt is typical for all the dishes for each course to be brought out together and placed around the perimeter of the Lazy Susan. It the turntable is large, a decorative centerpiece may occupy the center, since any food placed there would be out of reach of a seated diner. Alternatively, shared table condiments such as soy sauce, hot sauce, vinegar, or sesame oil may be located at the center.\n\nIf the dishes come out one at a time or if there is some special delicacy, they are typically served to the guest of honor first and then rotated clockwise around the table. The host will often wait to serve himself last. Dishes should typically not be removed from the Lazy Susan and placed on the table: at most, one should hold the dish aloft while serving and then return it to its place on the tray. One should try to avoid moving the Lazy Susan even slightly when someone is in the act of transferring food from the dishes to their plate or bowl. \n\n===Alcohol===\nWater and other non-alcoholic beverages may be consumed at any time. However, in formal settings, alcohol should only be consumed during [[toast (honor)|toasts]]. A modest toast may be followed by a single sip of wine or swallow of beer, but a ''baijiu'' toast is often ended with ''Ganbei!'' ({{lang|zh|\u5e72\u676f}}), an exhortation to drain the glass. Ideally, glasses are refilled immediately following a toast in preparation for the next.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn informal settings, individuals may order their preferred drinks. Carbonated beverages or beer are often ordered, although many diners may be satisfied with tea or hot water.\n\n==Bill (check)==\nThe bill for the meal (often call the \"check\") is presented at the end of the meal, after all the food and drinks have been served. In most restaurants in Chinese countries, there is no [[gratuity|tip]] expected unless it is explicitly posted. Usually if there is a tip required, it will already be added to the bill. However, in Chinese restaurants in North America tips are usually expected, as is customary in other restaurants of the region.\n\nIt is a common sight for families to dispute over who pays the bill, as the person paying thereby demonstrates generosity, sincerity, and dominance. If somebody organizes a meal and invites the guests, that person is usually accorded the honor of paying for the event.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Customs and etiquette in Japanese dining]]\n*[[Chinese culture|Culture of China]]\n*[[Chinese cuisine]]\n*[[Etiquette in Asia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n<!--\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=Jt6u8RZw51cC&pg=PA109&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false Ref. 8]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=Jt6u8RZw51cC&pg=PA109&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false Ref. 9]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=0TV8ebayzNUC&pg=PA26&dq=chinese+table+manners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JjgsT7FHg8qEB4fynIUD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=chinese%20table%20manners&f=false Ref. 10]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=npxUXbUg6uUC&pg=PA164&dq=chopstick+manners&hl=en#v=onepage&q=chopsticks&f=false Ref. 11 page 164]\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=32uyAAAAIAAJ&q=chopstick+etiquette&dq=chopstick+etiquette&hl=en Ref. 12 page 69-71]\n-->\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/28/business/global/28iht-busnav28.html?partner=rssnyt&emc=rss In China, Social Evenings Are Considered Part of the Business Routine]\n* [https://ac.els-cdn.com/S2352618115000657/1-s2.0-S2352618115000657-main.pdf?_tid=698dab50-0114-4938-a7f6-58bddca2b29a&acdnat=1528346775_0fcf187161655a2b6fe6aeb18defa85f Food, eating behavior, and culture in Chinese society]\n* [http://confuciusmag.com/chinese-dining-etiquette Chinese dining etiquette]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chinese Table Manner}}\n[[Category:Etiquette by region|Chinese dining]]\n[[Category:Dining etiquette]]\n[[Category:Chinese cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "Punkpumpking", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTable and place settings:adding some information about the preferred usage of vinegar and soy sauce in Chinese dishes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Customs_and_etiquette_in_Chinese_dining"}
